  "prompt": "Why are liquids not allowed on flights?",
  "response": "Liquids are restricted on flights primarily due to security concerns. This policy was implemented after a foiled terrorist plot in 2006, where liquid explosives were planned to be used to target transatlantic flights. Since then, regulations have been put in place to minimize the risk of liquid explosives being brought onto aircraft.\n\nPassengers are typically limited to carrying liquids in containers of 100 milliliters (3.4 ounces) or less, and these containers must be placed in a clear, resealable plastic bag not exceeding one liter in capacity. This allows security personnel to more easily inspect and manage the liquids.\n\nThe restrictions help ensure the safety and security of all passengers and crew by reducing the potential threat posed by liquid explosives.",
